1. What specialties do we have?

mt_samples |>
  count(medical_specialty, sort = TRUE) |>
  datatable(
    options = list(pageLength = 10)
  )

There are 40 different categories under the medical_specialty column. Most of the categories are medical specialties. Some of the categories are not linked to a specialty and are just describing the type of medical document (e.g.Â âConsult - History and Phy.â, âSOAP / Chart / Progress Notesâ, âDischarge Summaryâ, âEmergency Room Reportsâ). The categories are not evenly distributed. Surgery is by far the most represented specialty in this dataset.

2. Tokenize the words and visualize.

library(forcats)

mt_samples |> 
  unnest_tokens(token, description) |>
  count(token) |>
  top_n(20, n) |>
  ggplot(aes(n,fct_reorder(token, n))) +
  geom_col()

Many of the top 20 most common words in the description are stop words (e.g.Â âandâ, âofâ, âtheâ). The other words make sense. There are direction words (âleftâ, rightâ, âbilateralâ) to specify which side of the body is affected. The other words, such as âpatientâ, âyearâ, âoldâ, and âhistoryâ are often used in the opening line of a description (âPatient is a X year old woman, with history of xâ). Pain is a common complaint.

3. Redo visualization, removing stopwords.

mt_samples |>
  unnest_tokens(token, description) |>
  anti_join(stop_words, by = c("token" = "word")) |>
  count(token) |>
  top_n(20, n) |>
  ggplot(aes(n,fct_reorder(token, n))) +
  geom_col()

We see that they saw more female than male patients. It seems like the text is describing the patientâs medical history or current medical problem. It seems like pain is the most common complaint. Many patients were seen for issues related to their cervical spine, chest, or coronary artery.

Tokenize into bi-grams.

mt_samples |>
  unnest_ngrams(ngram, description, n = 2) |>
  count(ngram) |>
  top_n(20, n) |>
  ggplot(aes(n,fct_reorder(ngram, n))) +
  geom_col()

These ngrams make sense given the context, as many of them include the word âpatientâ. However, these ngrams do not provide much insight into the nature of these visits. Many of these ngrams are combinations of different stop words.

mt_samples |>
  unnest_ngrams(ngram, description, n = 3) |>
  count(ngram) |>
  top_n(20, n) |>
  ggplot(aes(n,fct_reorder(ngram, n))) +
  geom_col()

Some of these tri-grams are combinations of the bi-grams, such as âthe patient isâ and âyear old femaleâ. These tri-grams provide more insight into the most common reasons for visit, including âanterior cervical discectomyâ, âshortness of breathâ, and âcoronary artery diseaseâ.

5. Pick a word from an bi-gram and count words that appear before and after it

# Words that appear after "left"
mt_samples |>
  unnest_ngrams(ngram, description, n = 2) |>
  separate(ngram, into = c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ") |>
  select(word1, word2) |>
  filter(word1 == "left") |>
  count(word2, sort = TRUE) |>
  datatable(
    options = list(pageLength = 10)
  )

For patients with a complaint on the left side of their body, these are likely the most affected body parts.

# Words that appear before "left"
mt_samples |>
  unnest_ngrams(ngram, description, n = 2) |>
  separate(ngram, into = c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ") |>
  select(word1, word2) |>
  filter(word2 == "left") |>
  count(word1, sort = TRUE) |>
  datatable(
    options = list(pageLength = 10)
  )

The words before âleftâ do not give much insight into patientsâ medical conditions, as many preceding words are stop words. However, it seems like catheterizations and angiographies were common procedures.

mt_samples |>
